WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:34.999 --> 00:00:35.999
.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.999
Good afternoon everyone.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.999
It’s a pleasure and an honor

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.999
to welcome President Dilma Rousseff

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.999
who is visiting us for the
first time at Princeton.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.999
It isn’t any secret that
the events in Brazil

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:59.999
since last year make this
visit especially significant.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.999
With the necessary brevity, but searching
for a bit of intellectual honesty

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.999
I must say that... I don’t
have my star today...

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.999
but I must say that I have great sympathy

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.193
for the original proposal that
brought the Worker’s Party

00:01:18.218 --> 00:01:20.999
(PT) to power at the beginning
of the last decade,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.099
in a political and economic
process that ended in 2016,

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:31.599
in a decisive moment... and still
indefinite... of Brazilian politics,

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:35.999
with the impeachment of
President Dilma Rousseff.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.999
It isn’t my intention, at
this time and in this space

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.999
to defend or critique the
diverse political actors who,

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.999
since at least what we call the “jornadas
de 2013” (2013 Protests) in Brazil,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.999
have been confronting a complex
social legacy of the previous decade,

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:58.999
when the Brazilian economy
grew exponentially,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.999
when we saw a still-unrecognized
income distribution in the country,

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.999
while, nonetheless, some of its structural
problems were never completely resolved,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.399
like corruption, which is
today the star of the media,

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:15.999
and especially elementary public education.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:17.999
In one form or another,

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.999
the expansion of the internal market and Brazil’s
new place on the international stage seemed,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.999
to many of us Brazilians,

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.999
a natural legacy of the Constitution
proclaimed in 1988,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.999
following the most recent
Brazilian dictatorship.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.999
In short, the rights of a society

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.999
that was rehearsing its first steps
toward a return to democracy,

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.000
are today what we find threatened.

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.459
The parliamentary coup
d’etat which brought the

00:02:50.484 --> 00:02:52.923
impeachment of President
Dilma Rousseff last year

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.999
symbolized the closing of a
cycle in Brazilian history,

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.999
or perhaps the opening of another cycle,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.999
in which the judicialization and the spectacularization
(or the mediatization) of Brazilian politics

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.999
create an environment of
instability and uncertainty

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
in relation to the future
of democracy in Brazil.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:17.999
The worst part of this spectacularization

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:22.999
is probably the lack of dialogue and
the irreversible polarization of positions.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.999
As if there were only two sides,
two enemy tribes.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.999
To make things worse, the
presumed corruptors...

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.999
Those that are in prison... are those
that have the most visibility.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.999
A strange situation:

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:42.999
the crooks say what they wish,
and society listens to them,

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.999
without the justice system even having
determined the guilt of those who were accused.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.999
The presence of President
Dilma Rousseff today in Princeton

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.999
is an effort to give voice to someone who
had her political trajectory interrupted,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.999
which is certainly not
a novelty in her life,

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.999
since she, herself,
alongside other leftist militants,

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.999
was imprisoned during
the military dictatorship

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.500
and lived, last year, a process of
impeachment that made many of us think

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:19.700
in the distance there can be
between legality and legitimacy.

