00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:39.999
During my life, I have
lived two coups d’etat,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:46.000
One military coup and
one parliamentary coup.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.999
A military coup has certain characteristics

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:58.999
which are basically the
suspension of all rights,

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:05.999
the right to organize, of expression, the
right to mobilize, and freedom of the press,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.999
but above all, the right to dissent.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.999
When you dissent in a military coup,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
you’re imprisoned, tortured,
isolated, exiled, and killed.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.700
A parliamentary coup is
different because...

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.999
we have to study and understand it...

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.999
because it’s a post-Cold War coup,

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.999
a coup that has a characteristic:

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.999
it doesn’t eliminate certain
democratic rights for all people;

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.999
it eliminates rights for some people.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:56.999
Many have identified the
existence of parliamentary coups,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.999
principally in Latin America,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:06.999
because in recent years, we can identify
at least three coups d’etat:

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.999
one in Honduras, one in Paraguay,
with President Lugo,

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.999
and one in Brazil: the impeachment
that took me from power.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.999
These coups are becoming a new way

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:30.000
that popular governments are being
destroyed in Brazil and Latin America.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:37.999
This is a process for which we have
to understand its raison d’etre,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:44.999
because understanding and comprehending
is the essential preliminary way

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
to be able to change a situation.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:55.999
That’s why I begin telling you
that the parliamentary coup

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.999
by virtue of an impeachment
without the crime of responsibility,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:07.000
was motivated by a few reasons.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.999
I’ll start with a symbolic reason:

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:21.999
the use of a strong misogyny

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.999
that characterizes a certain typification
and certain instruments

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:32.000
which are going to be used against me
throughout the process.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.999
I always say

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:42.000
that what is done with words
is very important.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.999
Because what is done with words burdens,

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.999
in a democratic society,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.999
part of political and ideological struggle

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:59.999
and a vision of the world
and a vision of society

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.999
of questions of gender... really,
of all sorts of questions.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.999
In my case, a dichotomy was visible.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.999
I was seen as a “hard woman.”

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:19.999
Women are “hard.” Men are “strong.”

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:27.999
Women are “susceptible
to emotional crises.”

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.999
Men, no. Men are “sensible.”

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.999
Women are “obsessive-compulsive”
about their work.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:43.999
Men are “efficient and determined” workers.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.999
This comes out at times,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:53.999
sometimes even in coarse language.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.999
This happened throughout the coup,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.999
functioning as its underlying discourse.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.999
It is interesting to note, however,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.999
that for being the first female president,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:17.999
I was a woman surrounded by kind men.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:25.999
My male administrative aides, who worked
alongside my female administrative aides

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:32.999
were people who maintained
a non-misogynistic standard.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.999
They maintained a standard of cooperation,

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.999
and it is important to note...

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:45.999
Because this makes it clear that Brasil
isn’t just misogyny and gender hatred.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:51.999
This is an underlying reason,

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.999
almost a syntax,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:59.999
but it isn’t the principal
reason of the coup.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.999
There’s a reason that
also has a characteristic

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:13.999
which mobilizes the
parliamentary part of the coup,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:18.999
and it’s expressed in the
recording that they made

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:25.999
of the talk between a senator
in favor of the coup, Romero Jucá,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:32.999
and a senator what was in the process
of being accused, named Sérgio Machado.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:39.999
In this conversation,
Senator Jucá tells Senator Machado:

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:50.999
“It’s necessary to remove the President because
she’s not going to control Operation Car Wash,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.999
she doesn’t want to impede it, so we need to
remove her from power to “stop the bleeding.”

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.999
The word “bleeding” is literal,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.999
“remove me from power” is also literal,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.999
and “impede the
investigations” is explicit.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.999
There was, without any
doubt, this intention,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:19.999
primarily between those who
politically articulated the coup.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:25.999
It is also clear that this
is an underlying reason.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.999
Not that it isn’t important...

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.999
What I am saying is that, along with other
factors, this creates the reasons for the coup.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.999
But they don’t entirely explain it.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:45.999
It was necessary for larger interests to
come together in sectors favoring the coup,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:52.999
of political parties that
made the coup possible.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.999
Which sectors are these?

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:02.999
I would say that in part, it’s the media, which
in Brasil is controlled by four or five families.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.999
And in part, it’s the market.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.999
This conjunction media-market
has an interest.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.999
What is the interest?

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:19.999
To frame Brazil from an economic,
political, and social point of view...

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.999
But above all, economic and social...

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:27.999
And I also believe

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:35.999
that there was a strong interest
in framing external Brazilian politics.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.999
The political segment in favor
of the coup, as I said,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:44.999
was made up in a significant part,
by the PMDB and the PSDB,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.999
federal deputies and senators.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:55.999
So this group got together
to frame Brazil in what?

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.999
To frame Brazil in a neoliberal project

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.999
that we had interrupted, which had
been around since (President) Collor,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.999
passing through Fernando Henrique Cardoso,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:12.999
and had been suspended:

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:19.999
suspended when President Luiz Inácio
Lula da Silva was elected in 2003.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:25.999
At that time, we discontinued
a process of accelerated privatization

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:31.999
which had occurred, for example, in
Argentina... and will continue to occur.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:40.999
Argentina is losing its
instruments of finance politics.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:49.999
Argentina emerges from the crisis, following
the failure of the government of Menem

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:56.999
with the integral loss of the
instruments of the Argentine State.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.999
We maintained three large banks:

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.999
one bank, which is the only bank that gives
long-term loans, which is the BNDES,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.000
one comercial bank on the
model of the large private banks,

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.999
and one finance bank,
which is the Caixa Econômica Federal,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.999
in addition to maintaining
Petrobras and Eletrobras.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:23.999
But above all, the capacity
to articulate social policies in Brasil.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.999
To develop social policies.
And this we did.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.999
These policies are characterized
by introducing the poor in the budget.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:39.999
For carrying out a project
of social inclusion,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.999
the expansion of our internal market...

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:52.999
A country with 200 million inhabitants has
great wealth in its internal market.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:59.999
And at the same time, guarantee for
the first time in recent years

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:07.999
that there be a politics of social inclusion,
income distribution, and reduction of inequality.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:12.999
And this wasn’t only the transference
of wealth via the Bolsa Família,

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.999
that we have, and which
is very important. Why?

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.999
Fourteen million families...
It oscillates entre 13.9 and 14 million...

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:31.999
It is important to say
that these 14 million families

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.999
can be multiplied by four, on average,

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:42.999
which makes 56 million people. It isn’t
trivial to make this type of policy.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:49.999
And it’s important to say that
people don’t live from the Bolsa Família,

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.999
which is something reported by the media.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.999
People work. It’s just that
what they make isn’t sufficient.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.999
So the Bolsa Família completes the gap.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.999
And this is the fundamental
idea of the Bolsa Família,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.999
which has requirements,
such as, for example,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:14.999
Families have to enroll their children
in school... 85% is the minimum diligence

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.999
that a family has to take care of its children
in order to maintain the Bolsa Família.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:25.999
It has to get vaccinations
...three required systematic vaccines...

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.999
And, when a woman is pregnant,

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.999
she has to carry out
three mandatory pre-natal exams.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.999
This way, we reduced death by diarrhea,

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.999
we reduced infant mortality.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:46.999
But above all, we brought Brazil out of the UN
Hunger Map in 2014... between 2013 and 2014.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.999
And we overcame extreme poverty in 2014,

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:59.999
when we exceeded the limit,
which we considered,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:05.999
which was $1.50 per day,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.999
so that no Brazilian was below this.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.999
It’s something important.
But it wasn’t just this that we did.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:19.999
No process of income distribution
exists without access to public services

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.999
and without increased
opportunities for people

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:31.999
in terms of their own education
and ability to find better work.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.999
We are talking about assuring certain access to
differentiated productive activities. Through what?

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Through professional education.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.999
It was a program we called Pronatec,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.999
The National Program of Technical
Education and Employment.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:58.999
We constructed this program, in
partnership with other industrial services,

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:03.999
services of industrial
education, the SENAI,

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.999
which is a service that trains
industry workers...

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:13.999
By the way, Preident Lula became a metal worker 
because he had been trained at SENAI.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:17.999
So we formed this partnership with the SENAI,
with the National Service of Agriculture,

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.999
with the National Transportation Service,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:25.999
and with our Federal Institutes of
Technological Instruction,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.999
and we formed this partnership.
We trained 20 million people.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.999
Becuase in Brazil it's important to say:

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:41.999
We broke with the previos project which
enacted social policy through pilot programs.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:45.999
But enacting social policy through pilot programs,
in a country with 200 million inhabitants,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:53.000
100 million of whom are poor,
means not doing anything.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:58.999
So, when we see the curve of
income distribution in Brazil,

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:02.999
of income distribution and of inclusion,

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:08.999
you’ll see that the periods of pilot
programs are periods of stagnation,

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.999
there’s no effect on poverty.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:19.999
We have to make policies in Brazil
for millions of people.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:24.999
So there’s no policy.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:26.999
And this is something very important,

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:33.999
which is that people
changed their perspective.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:38.999
We have to remember that Brazil was the
last country to abolish slavery.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.999
I always say this because
it’s important for understanding Brazil.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:49.999
We have a problem with social inclusion
and we have a problem with privilege.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:55.999
There are segments of society
that think that it’s their privilege,

00:21:56.000 --> 00:21:59.999
for example, to enjoy the airports,

00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:04.999
without being disrupted by
domestic workers and doormen,

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:11.999
or other professional categories that before didn’t
travel in plane and started to travel in plane.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.999
But that’s just a detail.
The fact is, we did this.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.000
The coup, for me, was a planned process.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.999
Planned also because we were
going against the grain:

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:33.999
when inequality was increasing
in the rest of the world,

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:35.999
in Brazil it was decreasing.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.999
All you have to do is
look at the Gini index.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.999
However, we didn't manage to take
all the necessary steps.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:50.999
so that along with income distribution,
we could change wealth distribution.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:53.999
We partially achieved
more equal distribution of wealth,

00:22:54.000 --> 00:23:03.999
because we created programs that guaranteed
access to housing for the poorest population.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:07.999
In truth, I think that the
biggest factor of the coup

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:12.999
is that it was inimaginable for the poor
to form part of the budget.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:21.999
We had done something... and I don’t
consider it an absurd alteration,

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:26.999
a radical alteration in the system...

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:33.999
But it was an expressive step, because for the first
time there was really income distribution in Brazil,

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:41.999
for the first time, there were social
policies, any government policy had a focus:

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:46.999
“We have to overcome poverty,
we have to overcome supreme poverty,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:52.999
We have to guarantee access
to quality public services.”

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:54.999
This is so important.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:00.999
I’m going to say this because I met
a student of Cuban origin here.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.999
Because I want to speak about
“Mais Médicos” (More Doctors),

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:11.999
and I’m grateful to the Cuban doctors, and to the Cuban
government for having sent to Brazil 11,000 doctors.

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:16.999
Brazil was a country that had 1.8 doctors
for every 1,000 inhabitants,

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:20.999
below the standards set by
the World Health Organization.

00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:27.999
From there, we tried to grow and we created
many problems with the medical segments

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.999
because of the problem of privilege.

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:37.999
And we brought to Brazil 18,260 doctors,

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:44.999
which made it possible to
attend 63 million Brazilians.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:48.999
Where? Not over there in the Amazon...

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:55.999
There too... but also in the periphery of
the largest city in Brazil, São Paulo,

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.999
in the periphery of the largest Brazilian cities, the
capitals, cities larger than 100,000 inhabitants.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:06.999
Using what? The same database that was
used in the process for the Bolsa Família

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:13.999
served also to cross medical assistance
with the database registrar.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:19.999
You can observe that we
distributed privileging

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:26.999
where the population had the greatest need because
they have the greatest socio-economic fragility.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:33.999
Now... all that couldn’t be this way.
It had to end.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:40.999
So what happens? The
economic crisis begins.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.999
Nobody can do anything... we succeeded for six years
at preventing the crisis from arriving to us.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:50.999
One thing is governing
at the rise of a cycle.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:55.999
Another thing is governing
when the crisis begins,

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:01.000
because the crisis stirs up
something they call distributive conflict.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:06.999
You’ll remember that in Brazil,
on the eve of impeachment,

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:11.999
it was substantiated by the yellow duck,

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.999
there on the Avenida
Paulista, a six-meter duck,

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:17.999
that was an undue copy of a Dutch duck,

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:26.999
that they placed on the Avenida Paulista,
the financial center of São Paulo,

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:33.999
saying “I don’t want to pay the duck.” That is,
“pay the duck,” in a distributive conflict,

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:39.999
is to pay the necessary part of the crisis,
which is an increase in taxes.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.999
There is no way to just cut costs,

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:47.999
Europe is proving this, ad nauseam. Why?

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:52.999
Because what happens
with austerity policies?

00:26:53.000 --> 00:27:01.999
You cut, cut, cut spending, you depress
the economy instead of restarting it.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:07.999
In Brazil, we needed to adapt. In crisis,
you always need to readjust spending.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:14.999
How, then, to increase taxes at the same time,
which in Brazil is a completely regressive system?

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:20.999
Because it’s a difficult thing
to pass tax reform in Congress.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:26.999
We tried three times, and then we started
sending isolated adjustments.

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:29.999
And the last one we sent was the CPMF,

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.999
which is a tax of 0.38% on
financial transactions,

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:42.999
which caused horror for the elite, because it
would make clear where tax fraude was happening.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:49.999
That’s why the CPMF was
battled and transformed

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:57.999
into one of the greatest threats to
civilization committed by my government.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:03.999
The threat was precisely realizing that
we had already charged a greater CPMF.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:09.999
It was realizing that (and we had 
already changed the CPMF before) 

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.999
the internal revenue service, from 
taxing all financial transactions,

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:17.999
knows who’s paying what for whom.
So it was a very complex process.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:25.999
I want to say that the media played an
important role in distorting the facts.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.999
The media said Brazil was broken:

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:32.999
“This government needs to leave
because it left Brazil broken.”

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:36.999
Now, this government that
“left Brazil broken”

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:43.999
was the government that
prevented Brazil from defaulting

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.999
with the International Monetary Fund (FMI),

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:48.999
which permitted that in 2002,
when we arrived to the government,

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:55.999
the FMI dictated Brazil’s
macro-economic policy.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:02.000
We payed off the Fund around 2006,

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.999
I believe that it was at
the beginning of 2006.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.999
Why? Because the government before Lula

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:14.999
had only $14 billion in reserves

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:20.999
and owed $16 billion to international
creditors, if I’m not mistaken.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:24.999
Anyway, we payed off the Fund.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:30.999
But in the period of 2003
until the day I left the government,

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.999
we accumulated $380 billion in reserves.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.999
No country is “broken” if
it pays its creditors.

00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:45.999
We didn’t simply pay our creditors, we had
enough money to honor our commitments.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:55.999
“The government is broken”...a government
isn’t broken if it honors its debt,

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.999
if it has the capacity to go into debt
and to charge taxes.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.999
So the government broke the country?
The government didn’t break the country.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.999
The government faced an economic crisis

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:15.999
that became the basis for a political
crisis. That is what happened.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:21.999
The government faced an economic crisis
and suffered a political crisis.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:24.999
Why? Because we had a program.

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:29.999
We won four elections with that program.

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:32.999
In this past election, it became clear,

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:36.999
because they believed until the last minute
that they were going to win,

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:42.999
but in the past election it became clear
that they hadn’t won the elections.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:44.999
So what’s the situation?

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:52.999
Four consecutive times they had
lost the opportunity to adopt the program

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:58.999
that they considered best for Brazil,
which is a neoliberal conservative program

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:03.999
which believes that we spend
too much on the poor.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:11.999
So much so that they called... until the moment they
realized the population didn’t share their view...

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:15.999
They called the Bolsa Família the “Bolsa
Esmola” (the Charity Scholarship),

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:22.999
until the moment they realized that they had created an
enormous campaign against the arrival of the doctors,

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:27.999
until they realized that the doctors
had the support of the population,

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:31.999
90% of the population supports
the presence of the doctors

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:38.999
and even says that they are very important because
“they take care of us, they check in, they do exams,

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.999
and they have a closer relationship.”

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:46.999
And this is really good because it
changes the standard of service.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.999
Besides, they praise the doctors a lot.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:52.999
I also want to record here
that they say Brazilian nurses

00:31:53.000 --> 00:32:00.999
have great professionalism and a great capacity for
service, but going back to what I was saying...

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:05.999
So, if Brazil wasn’t broken,

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:12.999
if it wasn’t the government, if it wasn’t the
policies of the government, what was it?

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:18.999
“We’re against the policies of the government,
we can’t wait until the election.”

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:23.999
So they created they conditions and
the environment for impeachment.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:27.999
How do you create the
environment for impeachment?

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:37.999
It’s interesting to signal what
an author named Naomi Klein says.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:41.999
She says the following, citing Friedman,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.999
and citing Friedman’s
evaluation of two circumstances:

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:54.999
One, the government of Pinochet (in Chile) and
two, the Falklands crisis for Margret Thatcher.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.999
She basically says the following:

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:11.999
It is very important when you’re in a moment of crisis,
because in crisis... I’m going to quote literally:

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:18.999
“Only a crisis... actual or perceived...
Produces real change.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:26.999
When that crisis occurs, the actions that are
taken depend on the ideas that are lying around.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.999
That, I believe, is our basic function:

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.999
to develop alternatives
to existing policies,

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.999
to keep them alive and available

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:46.999
until the politically impossible
becomes the politically inevitable.”

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:52.999
The politically imposible was,
through the electoral process

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:58.999
to pass through the neoliberal reforms
that are now being imposed.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:03.999
They would never be approved.
They were never approved,

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:08.999
they were not even mentioned.

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.999
This is the politically impossible.

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:19.999
The politically inevitable is when a political crisis
on top of an economic crisis, creates impeachment.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:24.999
This is the trajectory and the prescription
of the coup in Brazil.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:30.999
It was about framing Brazil in
neoliberalism, and they did it.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:35.000
So I tell you here, concluding.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:34:52.999
This process is a process that is contradictory
today with the interests of the population.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:59.999
Why? After the impeachment,
they tried to limit the debt ceiling

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:03.999
which ends up freezing for 20 years
spending on education and health.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:13.999
In real terms, the rest of the
spending a primary budget exemptions

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.999
could even have nominal reduction.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.999
They propose a welfare reform,
which is the reform of a model

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:25.999
in which if you complete the
requirements for integral retirement,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:30.999
if you retire, you have
to start working at age nine.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.999
Why? It’s 65 years plus
49 years of service.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:41.999
49 years of service in a labor market with unemployment
and informality, you have seven more years, on average.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:47.999
Add 49 and 7, it makes 56, subtract
from 65, you get nine years old.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:50.999
It’s not evil, it’s changing the model.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.999
It’s getting rid of public welfare,

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.999
creating the conditions
to privatize welfare.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.999
But in the interim, it destroys retirement
for women, rural workers, men, the poor,

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:07.999
it gets ride of assistance
for the poor and disabled.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.999
It creates job insecurity
with the law they call outsourcing,

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:19.999
it increases deregulation of the job market,
creating job insecurity and diminishing salaries

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:24.999
now through a project that
wants to do away with

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.999
the Consolidation of Labor Laws (CLT),
of workers’ protections.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:37.999
Anyway, it opens up land to foreigners, opens
the skies to aviation without a counterbalance

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:45.999
it’s selling parts of the pre-salt layer
at rather questionable prices...

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.999
and all of this is happening.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:53.999
What’s the contradiction? The more they do
this to serve the media and the market,

00:36:54.000 --> 00:37:02.999
the more the population reacts against
them, and there they have a conflict.

00:37:03.000 --> 00:37:07.999
There’s an election in 2018.
The conflict is the following:

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:14.999
If it serves the market, the congresspeople
who aren’t suicidal

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.999
(they might be something else,
but they aren’t suicidal)

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:21.999
they won’t vote in such unpopular measures.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:26.999
If they don’t vote, they won’t deliver
service to the market.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:33.999
If they vote... the congresspeople
who aren’t suicidal...

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:38.999
There’s no proof of the
measures they need to deliver.

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:40.999
That’s the dilemma.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:49.999
Besides that, even though they had promised that they would
freeze the investigations so they wouldn’t reach them

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:51.999
they reached them.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.999
So, the situation in Brazil
today only has one solution.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:04.999
That old story that it’s possible to talk,
to have dialogue, is a fairy tale.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:10.999
No one can think that in a country 
with the complexity of Brazil,

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:12.999
everybody is going to sit down and talk.

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:18.999
Where do we talk in a democracy?
In the election we talk.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:25.999
So, the only way to get out of this crisis
in which we find ourselves is the election.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:29.999
Be that when it is, it’s a
scheduled meeting in a democracy.

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:36.999
If it isn’t before, we know that
there’s a date scheduled: October of 2018.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:40.999
And October of 2018 in
Brazil already began.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:47.999
Why? Because the national
campaign mobilizes all interests.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:51.999
It’s like this here too. Presidential
regimes have this characteristic.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:39:03.999
I believe that the only way out for Brazil is democracy,
more democracy, and greater extension of freedoms.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:08.999
And remembering always that we have
only transformed a country successfully

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:11.499
when we’ve had democracy.

00:39:11.500 --> 00:39:12.999
They’ve been the richest periods.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.000
Thank you very much.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:12.000
Thank you very much.
Everyone can hear, right?

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.999
We’re going to move to the questions.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:21.999
We have approximately 20-25 minutes.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:27.999
Believe me that it’s not an easy task
to cut off the President...

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:32.999
but I think this way,
we’ll have a little time.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:34.999
The organization we had discussed

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:39.999
is that we are going to
collect a few questions

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:44.999
so there’s more time for the
voice to be with you all.

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:50.999
I’m going to use my prerogative as moderator
to ask the first question very quickly,

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:53.999
which is, simply: Mrs. President,

00:40:54.000 --> 00:41:00.999
for us to get beyond the idea
of the inevitability of the coup,

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:06.999
how can we think about
and understand retrospectively

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:14.999
the 2013 protests in Brazil?

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:16.999
There are microphones in the audience.

