00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:50.999
and which is due to this yearning for more.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:56.999
And I also believe that there’s
something interesting about Brazil.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:01.999
There’s an institute called “Data Popular”

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:11.999
that ran an investigation about what
you attribute a change in your life to.

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:13.999
In the first place, God.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:18.999
In the second place, the person, him
or herself... which is very good.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:23.999
In the third place, the person’s family.
In the fourth place, a few friends,

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:28.999
and in the last place, the government.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:36.999
I’m saying this because it isn’t only my
information, it didn't happened only in Brazil.

00:46:37.000 --> 00:46:46.999
I had a conversation recently with
ex-President Cristina Kirchner

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:50.999
and she tells that me in Argentina
the pattern of response is very similar.

00:46:51.000 --> 00:46:52.999
What does this mean?

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:58.999
It means that governments
can’t stop doing things,

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:01.999
explaining why they are
doing certain things.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:08.999
Principally because when they’re large-scale
policies, it isn’t clear what is being done.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:13.999
So there was dissatisfaction
toward access to services. Very strong.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.999
I also think that at that time,

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:24.999
there was a theory that it was
legitimate democratic expression.

00:47:25.000 --> 00:47:28.999
That’s how we confronted it at the time.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:34.999
We treated it as something necessary,
something correct.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:42.999
I don’t think 2013 had anything
to do with 2016 and 2015.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:47.999
Why? Because in 2013, Brazil was growing.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.999
The interest rate had reached 2.5%.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:52.999
The unemployment rate was falling.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:58.999
So immediate economic reasons,
there weren’t any.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:02.999
But I think there was
social dissatisfaction

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:10.999
caused by improvements in quality of life
and greater necessity for change.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:16.999
That’s why I think that
2013 has a component

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.999
that is a positive component,
not a negative component.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:27.999
I believe that the resurgence of the idea of
"the worse the better" doesn’t come in a vacuum.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:29.999
It’s not a flash in a blue sky.
It’s human-powered.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.999
And here I move to the second (question).

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.999
They choose a president of the Chamber,

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:39.999
a president of the Chamber who changes...
And I’ll move also to the other question...

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:43.999
Who changes the democratic
center of Brazil.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:50.999
You have a democratic center that emerges
from the Constitution of 1988

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:56.999
of which Dr. Ulysses Guimarães, aka "Democratic
Elections Doctor," holds its maximum expression.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:00.999
So you have a pattern with Brazil’s
center being progressive.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:05.999
And besides being progressive, it participated
in one form or another in all governments.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:10.999
All the presidential
coalitions of the moment.

00:49:11.000 --> 00:49:13.999
Beginning at a certain moment,
there’s a rupture in this center.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:18.999
Its hegemony shifts to a
position on the extreme right,

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:22.999
ultraconservative from
the point of view of civilization,

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:28.999
and representative of the “Bancada da
Bala,” of the “Boi” (the “BBB Bench”).

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:33.999
It’s BBB, right? Bullet,
bullock, and bible.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:35.999
Those three.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:39.999
And there are gender politics
that are very bad.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:46.999
Homophobic politics,
besides being ultra ultra conservative

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.999
and neoliberal.

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:54.999
This political hegemonization
invalidated my government,

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:56.999
four months after being elected.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:02.999
March. I was elected in November. In March, they
already brought to the table the idea of impeachment.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:07.999
From there, politics in terms of
worse and better is visible.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:09.999
The enterprise called it
the “Pauta-Bomba” (Bombs Away!).

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.999
It was the agenda that
increased spending instead of reducing.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:17.999
So I don’t think it had
anything to do with 2013

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:21.999
but I think that ascending
technocratic politics

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:26.999
have plagued Brazil since the dictatorship.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.999
This politics they call technocratic,

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:37.999
something above good and evil, and that
we have to elect technocratic leaders,

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:42.999
Comes from the dictatorship.
The dictatorship created this,

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:48.999
in that old discussion that a student
was for studying, a teacher for teaching

00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:54.999
a worker for working, and politics
was carried out by a military government.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:51:00.999
So this process by a technocratic
government, apolitical and not ideological,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.999
that is the vision. And I think
this is very serious.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:09.999
Because I think that anyone who defends
one of these positions isn’t democratic.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.999
Democracy is born for politics.

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:16.999
You can’t separate one from the other. Why?

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:22.999
Because without a political vision
in the sense of defending interests,

00:51:23.000 --> 00:51:29.999
not my individual interests, but
the collective interests of a society,

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:33.999
you don’t have a democratic process.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:39.999
There’s no given form by the economy

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:44.999
nor by any economic, sociological,
or political theory

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:51.999
that guarantees the correct
management of men and women.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:56.999
There is only one way:

00:51:57.000 --> 00:51:59.999
politics, conscience,
opposition, and participation.

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:05.999
So, technocracy is a very
questionable form of domination

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:09.999
that I think emerges today
from the following contradiction:

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:13.999
neoliberalism, increasing inequality,

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:18.999
and increasing restrictions.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:24.999
It’s a form of corroding democracy.
One of the variables is technocracy.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:31.999
To say that it’s possible
to look in the manual,

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:36.999
and get rid of participation of the 
people with their votes, or to take

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:44.999
care of the public sphere technocratically, 
is impossible to carry out democratically.

00:52:45.000 --> 00:52:49.999
In any dictatorship, this is a no-brainer.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:54.999
The list... So what happens?

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:00.999
The list isn’t of 81 people.
The list is of 300 people.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:05.999
They’re being sent to investigation.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:10.999
They’re not being prosecuted.
What’s the problem?

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:15.999
Many problems come out of this.
I’m not going to tell here.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:19.999
I really should, so I’m going to.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:25.999
You know why I should tell? Because it shows
a certain pattern for you to understand.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:31.999
During one year, two
people from my campaign,

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:38.999
one was the treasurer, and another was
the person who became my chief of staff,

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:49.999
were accused of having gone to the CEO
of a company called Andrade Gutierrez,

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:55.999
the CEO was named Otávio Azevedo. I’m saying
the names because they’re public record.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:59.999
He said that these members of my campaign,

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:04.999
had gone there and threatened:

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:08.999
“If you don’t contribute to the campaign,
you won't get any contracts.”

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.999
No position in the government.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:15.999
This is how it was taken.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:21.999
So the judge... a little more
than a year went by...

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:28.999
And the judge calls this man
to testify, and asks,

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:32.999
and the defense attorney also asks,

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:36.999
“When was this?” He says the date.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:40.999
“And how was it done?”
With a nominal cheque.

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:44.999
“What day was it?” He gives the date.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.999
If I’m not mistaken,
it was a 10th or a 14th.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:53.999
The people from the campaign go
check the records,

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.999
because it was an official action.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:01.999
Bribe and blackmail,
that was the only charge.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:05.999
So they go there and
discover the following:

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:09.999
There was, in fact, a donation and
there was, in fact, a nominal cheque.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:12.999
For whom was the donation?

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:14.999
It was for the PMDB.

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.999
Why did he think it was for the PT?

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:24.000
Because the in the court classification, the last number 
of the process was 13 [number of the Workers' Party, PT].

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.333
Wait, be calm. You
think it stopped there?

00:55:28.358 --> 00:55:30.999
If it were only that, we
would have been condemned.

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:36.999
So he looks for the nominal cheque...
And this is all online.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:43.999
It was published in all the newspapers,
by Jânio de Freitas, nonetheless.

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:48.999
So they look at the nominal cheque.
To whom is it made out?

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.999
Michel Temer.

00:55:52.000 --> 00:55:57.999
So then we told the judge:
“Cancel the accusation,

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:02.999
"call out the person who had pressed 
charges, this is perjury.”

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:07.999
So the judge calls the person 
who had pressed charges

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:11.499
and asks him:

00:56:11.500 --> 00:56:14.999
“Here is the evidence,
do you have anything to say?”

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:18.999
And he says, “Oops, I was mistaken.”

00:56:19.000 --> 00:56:21.999
The defense says, "How is it possible
that you made a mistake,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:26.999
"if you said for a year that this was corruption?"

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:31.999
"You said it was. Now it isn’t corruption anymore?
We would like to know if it was corruption."

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:36.999
He hadn’t just been mistaken,
but this wasn’t corruption.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:56:44.999
It hadn’t happened. No one went and
looked for him in his office.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:48.999
And this is what I’m saying:

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:51.999
A lot of things are pushed through quickly.

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:55.999
When you treat some people, it’s
according to certain criteria

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.999
and when you treat others,
it’s different criteria.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:05.999
I think it’s very strange that
during those two and a half years

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:12.999
The accused have only been from the PT.
Only.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:15.999
Now it’s imposible for everyone else
not to be investigated too.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:18.999
I want to tell you all,

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:23.999
I want to say this because it’s 
been broadcast to Brazil as well,

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:27.999
that with me, they use a trick
which is the following:

00:57:28.000 --> 00:57:32.999
“She knew.” And then you ask,
“But did you tell her this?”

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:39.999
“No I didn’t, but she should have known.”

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:42.999
“But how should she have known?”

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:46.999
And here it’s the judge asking:
“How should she have known? Why?”

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:49.999
Because of the size of my enterprise.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:53.999
So they accuse me. They can’t accuse
me of having given money.

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.999
They can’t accuse me of having
a Swiss bank account

00:57:57.000 --> 00:58:00.999
of money in any other fiscal paradise.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:06.999
They can’t accuse me of having accepted

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.999
ANY illegal action.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:13.999
Now, accusations of the sort,
“She should have known”

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:18.999
I’ve had since the day of my election.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:23.999
On the day of my election, the cover
of the magazine Veja read:

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:27.999
“She knew everything.”

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:31.999
It didn’t specify what was this
“everything” nor what I “knew.”

00:58:32.000 --> 00:58:35.999
The advantage now is that
this is going to be opened up.

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:41.999
And just like we discovered the
nominal cheque and the account,

00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:47.999
we’ll discover what type of story this is.
So I think I've finished...

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:50.999
Ah, and Vinícius and infrastructure.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:54.999
Vinícius, terrible news: they’re
destroying the BNDES.

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:58.999
The BNDES is being destroyed.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:03.999
First they went and took
$100 billion from the BNDES.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:05.999
Why? How does the BNDES work?

00:59:06.000 --> 00:59:09.999
Part of the BNDES obtains resources;

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:14.999
it has shares, it
participates in companies.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:19.999
All this creates cash flow.

00:59:20.000 --> 00:59:23.999
Another part is that the union government

00:59:24.000 --> 00:59:28.999
increases its participation.

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:33.999
It increases the quantity of resources

00:59:34.000 --> 00:59:41.999
that it sends to the BNDES
to be able to make loans.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:43.999
It was always like this
and always worked like this.

00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:46.999
One of the things that allowed us to have

00:59:47.000 --> 00:59:50.999
fairly high economic growth in this period

00:59:51.000 --> 00:59:55.999
wasn’t for us, it was from
financing activities.

00:59:56.000 --> 00:59:59.999
From small activities
to more sophisticated ones.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.999
And this was done with the BNDES.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:07.999
I think the BNDES is a
fundamental instrument of development.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:13.999
For you to have an idea, the resources of the BNDES
were of the size of the resources of the World Bank.

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:20.999
The BNDES isn’t a little bank. Many times bigger
than the Inter-American Development Bank.

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:23.999
In terms of resources, very
close to the World Bank.

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:28.999
In this period, the
government didn’t take loans,

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:32.999
not from the BID, nor from the World Bank.

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:36.999
We left the BID and the World Bank

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:41.999
for states and regional
governments, if necessary.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:49.999
Starting in 2007-2008, we never took
any more resources because we had them.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:52.999
Brazil is a rich country.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:57.999
Believe me that what they’re
doing is the following:

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:02.999
they are constructing a new brutal recession
because they believed in their own story.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:09.999
First, they believed that the economic crisis
was due to the PT being in the government

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:13.999
and not because there was a huge drop
in the price of commodities.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:22.999
You had the United States leaving the TPP, provoking
a generalized crisis in emerging countries.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:27.999
In Brazil, we were still feeling the
effects of the recession in China.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:32.999
China is an important economy
for emerging countries.

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:37.999
And Brazil went through its
biggest hydrological crisis...

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:42.999
We’re still at the end of it...
In the past 80 years.

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.999
We had drought for a long time
where had never been drought,

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:51.999
which was in São Paulo, in the
southeast of the country.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:55.999
And this provoked an extreme
situation of inflation,

01:01:56.000 --> 01:02:01.999
because we had to drop the
price of thermal energy.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:04.999
We use more water. You don’t pay for water.
When you use thermal energy,

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:07.999
you pay for fuel, and fuel is expensive.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:11.999
This had repercussions in
prices and in inflation.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.999
And finally, what I think
is most significant

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:18.999
is that they underestimated the
political crisis they created,

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:20.999
which is very serious.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.999
Mrs. President, we are unfortunately out
of time, as we are aware.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:27.999
But I’d like to ask just one last question
to be able to close,

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:31.999
and the question is very simple,
and from the bottom of my heart.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:36.999
Thinking about Brazil, and the future,

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:40.999
and not thinking only about 2018,

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:44.999
although we’re all tempted to think 
about a big change in 2018,

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:50.999
how to be optimistic today
and recover utopia?

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.999
I don’t think 2018 will bring a big change.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:57.999
I think 2018 is something else.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:01.999
Brazil has a tradition of
making transitions on top.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.999
I’ll give the the last one,
but we could cite several.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:08.999
In the last one, despite the movement 
in support of free elections after the dictatorship,

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:13.999
when there would be a democratic transition, 
a renegotiation was made.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:18.999
And I’m not saying here that
it should have been different.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.999
I think we cannot do that with history.
It was like that.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:23.999
It was like that. What did they do?

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:29.999
They negotiated torture. The torturers
were going to get amnesty.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:33.999
There were many arguments that if you didn’t
do this, a transition wouldn’t be possible.

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.999
Nobody will ever know.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:40.999
The fact is that we’re different
from Argentina, Chile, and Uruguay,

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:44.999
which didn’t give amnesty to torturers
and prosecuted them.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:47.999
The consequence of this
is that it’s possible

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:52.999
for a person to go inside Parliament to
defend the military dictatorship and torture

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:54.999
in a vote for impeachment.

01:03:55.000 --> 01:03:59.999
And others invade the parliament and
defend the return of a military dictatorship.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:04.999
This would be unthinkable in Chile,
Uruguay, and Argentina.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:09.999
Anyway, I don’t think it’s possible today
to make a transition on top.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:15.999
A transition on top is a
transition of the elite.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:18.999
I think that always in a transition,

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:22.999
there has to be a base in which all the people

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:26.999
and leaders participate.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:28.999
I understand that.

01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:30.999
I just think that at this time,

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:37.999
there has to be a democratic process
as the basis of any transition.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:42.999
Any negotiation, any dialogue,
if you want to use the word.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:44.999
Any dialogue.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:46.999
There will never be dialogue,

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:49.999
because it isn’t possible to have dialogue,

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:53.999
without a democratic process.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:56.999
I don't think it's a return to power,
or to remain there.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:04:58.999
I just believe the following:

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:03.999
Without a democratic process
with participation by the population...

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:07.999
And win whoever wins,
the result must be respected.

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:12.999
This is the only possible way
to have a transition.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:17.999
The democratic process for me is much more,

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:23.999
the detonator of a process that will
allow Brazil to retake a path.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:27.999
If it’s going to be 2018?
It’s the deadline.

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:29.999
I don’t know when it’s going to occur,

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:31.999
it will depend on the country’s situation.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:35.999
But I think that there’s
a date scheduled in 2018.

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:41.999
And from this effect, alongside the process,
comes another thing: political reform.

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:46.999
Because a country with 25
parties is ungovernable.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:51.999
It’s not that people aren’t virtuous.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:54.999
They might even not be very virtuous.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:56.999
But the electoral system,

01:05:57.000 --> 01:05:58.999
the political system,

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:03.999
triggers non-virtue.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:07.999
Why? Because 25 parties
can’t have a program.

01:06:08.000 --> 01:06:11.999
I’m sorry, but there are not
25 programs for Brazil.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:16.999
And it’s not 25, it will
be 30 very soon.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:19.999
Why? Because they got rid
of the electoral threshold,

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:23.999
so two democratic clauses,

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:26.999
which are free access to communication
media during the electoral period,

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.999
which gets rid of the media filter,

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:34.999
and the public party fund
that gives support,

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:41.999
those two are obviously used
for the expansion of parties.

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:45.999
If the party is free, and I’m
going to have access to the party fund,

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:49.999
and I can negotiate time on TV,
I can aim at what I want for the party.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:52.999
Since I am never going to be in power

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:57.999
because I’m from a tiny party,

01:06:58.000 --> 01:06:59.999
what do I do?

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:01.999
I negotiate positions, I negotiate amendments,

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:05.999
I negotiate advantages.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:11.999
So it has to do with the process
of ungovernability in Brazil.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:15.999
This is where (and I don’t know how you 
translate physiology in the United States)

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:17.999
Or patronage.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:20.999
Do you know how to translate it?

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:24.000
I think it already entered into
the vocabulary, didn’t it?

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.999
Yes. This is a process
that the system fosters.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:33.999
So two things have to occur.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:38.999
The democratic process, you never know...

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:41.999
you never know what comes
out of the judge’s head.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:46.999
It used to be said that you never know 
what comes from a judge's head...but you know. 

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:48.999
From a woman’s womb, you also know.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:51.999
But the electoral process you 
never know what will come.

01:07:52.000 --> 01:07:54.999
You can’t know. It’s impossible.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:58.999
And also, at this stage, to say that 
democracy is a threat...

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:05.999
I already mentioned this story I'd heard in the past.
Democracy is not a threat!

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:09.999
At this moment, democracy is
the only way to structure a process

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:14.999
that didn’t work out, which is the
impeachment process,

01:08:15.000 --> 01:08:18.999
the coup, and the
consequences of the coup.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:23.999
The absolute paralysis today of Brazil
facing everything that is happening.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:27.999
They’re not giving anything, they’re not
even delivering anything to the market.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:31.999
We’re in a rather difficult situation.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:33.999
So I say for you here:

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:35.999
I believe that in the democratic process

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:38.999
there’s no shame in losing the election.

01:08:39.000 --> 01:08:44.999
There’s no shame in the election
for whoever wins and whoever loses.

01:08:45.000 --> 01:08:47.999
What’s wrong is losing the election

01:08:48.000 --> 01:08:50.999
and wanting to win by other means.

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:53.999
That’s what’s wrong.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:57.999
So for me, the democratic
process is eminently...

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:00.999
Now, they can’t create a coup

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:03.999
in a democratic process. 

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:09.999
The democratic process's aim is 
for us to find ourselves.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:12.999
Because nobody can start saying
after an election,

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:17.999
“But I don’t want that president,
I want the other one”

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:23.999
Because if not, you shake things up
and then there’s a coup.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:28.999
So on top of this, on top of
the democratic process

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:31.999
you make a pact.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:33.999
Because I don’t think,
and you’ll excuse me...

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:36.999
I already told this story yesterday,

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:40.999
I always remember a cartoon I read
of Asterix and Obelix.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:45.999
There’s the centurion mounted on the horse,

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:50.999
pensive and reflective,
and he says the following:

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:55.999
“I think these Welsh are really strange.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:09:59.999
“We invade their country,

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:02.999
“We destroy their towns

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:07.999
“We kill them, we rape their women,

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:11.999
“And when we want dialogue,
they don’t want to talk.”

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:14.999
I’m so sorry, but in order to
have dialogue today in Brazil,

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:17.999
you have to have popular participation.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:19.999
There is no dialogue on top possible.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:24.999
There’s an agreement. What is it?
The agreement is the following:

01:10:25.000 --> 01:10:26.999
We are going to have direct elections.

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:28.999
We are going to make political reform.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:33.999
I think this agreement
is absolutely necessary.

01:10:34.000 --> 01:10:36.999
Now, dialogue is dialogue.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:41.000
First and foremost, you have to have
a basis of democracy.

